<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="158" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,773,689,2023]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">
All material examined. Numeric phenotypical data were recorded in 81 nest samples with 
<specimenCount box="[636,771,1009,1031]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" type="worker">381 workers</specimenCount>
and 30 gynes. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:F52B87F65E2F6158FF5ED83FFC4A1C99:785D603B5E2F6158FEE6DE50FEFE1D19" box="[303,367,1041,1063]" country="Austria" county="The" municipality="For" name="These" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">These</location>
originated from 
<collectingCountry box="[546,627,1041,1063]" name="Austria" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Austria</collectingCountry>
(17 samples), Czechia (three), 
<collectingCountry box="[336,423,1073,1095]" name="Finland" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Finland</collectingCountry>
(24), Scotland (one), 
<collectingCountry box="[667,771,1073,1095]" name="Mongolia" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
(five), 
<collectingCountry box="[225,313,1105,1126]" name="Norway" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Norway</collectingCountry>
(three), 
<collectingCountry box="[415,491,1105,1127]" name="Russia" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Russia</collectingCountry>
(19), 
<collectingCountry box="[560,647,1105,1127]" name="Sweden" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Sweden</collectingCountry>
(one), and 
<collectingCountry box="[151,287,1137,1159]" name="Switzerland" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
(eight). 
<collectingMunicipality box="[384,422,1137,1158]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">For</collectingMunicipality>
details, see SI1, SI2, and SI3. 
<collectingCounty box="[151,192,1169,1191]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">The</collectingCounty>
total number of samples numerically or subjectively investigated was 130.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="158" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,773,689,2023]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">
Geographic range. Eurosiberian-boreomontane. Continuous range from 
<collectingCountry box="[421,771,1265,1287]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Northern Ireland and Scotland</collectingCountry>
to 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:F52B87F65E2F6158FF5ED83FFC4A1C99:785D603B5E2F6158FF7CDF50FEAD1C19" box="[181,316,1297,1319]" country="United Kingdom" county="Eastern Alps" latitude="63.0" longLatPrecision="0" longitude="9.0" municipality="Bohemian Forest" name="East Siberia" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">East Siberia</location>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[332,409,1297,1318]" degrees="131" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" precision="55555" value="131.0">131° E</geoCoordinate>
), in Fennoscandia between 56.3 and 
<geoCoordinate box="[201,267,1329,1350]" degrees="71" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" precision="55555" value="71.0">71° N</geoCoordinate>
, and in Siberia between 47.5 and 
<geoCoordinate box="[650,718,1328,1350]" degrees="63" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" precision="55555" value="63.0">63° N</geoCoordinate>
. The montane range in Europe extends from SE to NW over the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:F52B87F65E2F6158FF5ED83FFC4A1C99:785D603B5E2F6158FF5EDF31FED51CB8" box="[151,324,1392,1414]" country="United Kingdom" county="Eastern Alps" latitude="63.0" longLatPrecision="0" longitude="9.0" municipality="Bohemian Forest" name="Rila Mountains" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">
Rila 
<collectorName box="[202,377,1392,1414]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Mountains, NW</collectorName>
</location>
Carpathians, 
<collectingMunicipality box="[531,720,1392,1414]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Bohemian Forest</collectingMunicipality>
, and the 
<collectingCounty box="[194,337,1424,1446]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Eastern Alps</collectingCounty>
westward to 
<geoCoordinate box="[489,542,1425,1446]" degrees="9" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" precision="55555" value="9.0">9° E</geoCoordinate>
. 
<collectorName box="[553,577,1425,1446]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">In</collectorName>
the 
<collectorName box="[629,678,1424,1446]" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Alps</collectorName>
ascending to 
<quantity box="[223,304,1457,1478]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" unit="m" value="2400.0">
<elevation box="[223,304,1457,1478]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" unit="m" value="2400.0">2400 m</elevation>
</quantity>
. Main distribution in the Alps within the autochthonous distributional area of 
<taxonomicName authority="(EICHHORN 1964)" baseAuthorityName="EICHHORN" baseAuthorityYear="1964" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Larix" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[574,637,1489,1510]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="158">Larix</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="EICHHORN" firstAuthor="EICHHORN" journalOrPublisher="Zeitschrift fur Angewandte Entomologie" pageId="25" pageNumber="158" pagination="253 - 289" part="43" refId="ref45382" refString="EICHHORN, O. 1964: Zur Verbreitung und Okologie der hugelbauenden Waldameisen. - Zeitschrift fur Angewandte Entomologie 43: 253 - 289." title="Zur Verbreitung und Okologie der hugelbauenden Waldameisen" type="journal article" year="1964">EICHHORN 1964</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
